Introduction:¶

In this session we are going to work with Apache Hive. Apache Hive is an open source software which facilitates reading, writing, and managing large datasets in distributed storage (HDFS/Hbase) using SQL-like queries.

  • Hive uses HiveQL.
  • it generates MapReduce jobs that run on Hadoop cluster.

Hive Basic operations:¶

Here are some operations that Hive can performs:

  • Create database
    • CREATE DATABASE d;.
    • CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS d;

  • Drop database
    • DROP DATABASE d;

  • Create table
    • CREATE TABLE tablename (colname DATATYPE, ...) ROW FORMAT DELIMITED FIELDS TERMINATED BY char LOCATION 'user/cloudera/a';

  • Querying table
    • sql queries e.g. SELECT a FROM B

  • Loading data
    • hdfs dfs -mv /a/b.txt /user/hive/warehouse/b/
    • INSERT INTO TABLE a SELECT * FROM b;

- To create partitioned table accounts_by_State¶

  • From Hive Shell run the following commands that will enable dynamic partitioning: 
    SET  hive.exec.dynamic.partition = true;
SET  hive.exec.dynamic.partition.mode = nonstrict;
SET hive.exec.max.dynamic.partitions.pernode=400;


  • CREATE Table accounts_by_State(
cust_id INT,
fname STRING,
lname STRING,
address STRING,
city STRING,
zipcode STRING
)
PARTITIONED BY (state STRING);



  • Load data into accounts_by_State 
    INSERT OVERWRITE TABLE accounts_by_State
PARTITION(state)
SELECT cust_id, fname, lname,address, city, zipcode, state 
FROM accounts;

Task 4: Data Bucketing¶

We will now need to practice bucketing of the data.

  • We have to create a bucketed table called accounts_in_buckets. We shall bucket on the state field(2 buckets)
  • We have to run an insert from select statement to load the data from the original accounts table into the new accounts_in_buckets table.
  • Finally, Retrieve the names of the customers in the CA,Oakland on the bucketed (clustered) table

Run those commands in terminal¶

set hive.exec.mode.local.auto.input.files.max=10
SET hive.enforce.bucketing = true

In [ ]:
#put your queries and screenshots here
In [ ]:
CREATE Table accounts_in_buckets(
cust_id INT,
fname STRING,
lname STRING,
address STRING,
city STRING,
state STRING,
zipcode STRING
)
CLUSTERED BY (state)  INTO 2 BUCKETS;
In [ ]:
INSERT OVERWRITE TABLE accounts_in_buckets
SELECT cust_id, fname, lname,address, city, state, zipcode 
FROM accounts;

Task 6: Change Storage Formats (No Grade)¶

We will use Hive to transform data formats from textual into other binary formats. We can transform the original accounts table into AVRO once and into Parquet another time.

  • create table accounts_avro and instruct Hive to store it as AVRO
  • Similarly, create table accounts_parquet
  • Load the data from the original table accounts into the target tables via insert from select statements
  • Finally, select customer names who lives in CA state from both tables to make sure that everything works fine.
In [ ]:
CREATE TABLE accounts_avro
STORED AS Avro
TBLPROPERTIES (
'avro.schema.literal'='{
  "type" : "record",
  "name" : "Accounts",
  "doc" : "Schema for the accounts_avro table",
  "fields" : [ {
    "name" : "cust_id",
    "type" : [ "int", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "fname",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "lname",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "address",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "city",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "zipcode",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "state",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  } ]
}'

);
In [ ]:
INSERT OVERWRITE TABLE accounts_avro
SELECT cust_id, fname, lname,address, city, zipcode, state 
FROM accounts;
